*July 01: The Rules Change. No Execptions*

10 changes take effect on 1 July across Verification & KYC, Account
Structure, Billing & Invoicing, and Cash Automation.
Why This Is Changing

Most of what's below comes down to one thing: making sure money, identity,
and account hierarchy all point to a single, verifiable source of truth.
Cash sitting in a wallet with no verified bank account behind it, riders
working public networks with no identity check, and child accounts quietly
drifting from their parent's billing setup have all been operational grey
areas until now.

From 1 July, they become rules the system enforces on its own.


Key Changes
Verification & KYC



*Inactive Riders Marked Automatically At Month-End*


Starting 30th June, the system will automatically mark riders inactive on a
periodic basis. Note that this isn't a one-time cleanup; it repeats
regularly to make sure the system stays clean and accounts do not have
bloated rider count.


Riders who haven't worked in a period of 30 days and hold no cash, would be
automatically marked inactive.


*Bank Verification Required Before Any COD Cash Is Paid Out*


From 1 July, a business needs verified bank details in system to receive th=
e
due from pidge amount back to them. Until verification is complete, the Due
From Pidge page will show a banner flagging this, and any attempt to turn
on T+1 remittance will be blocked. This applies wherever COD orders are
involved.


Pidge ends up holding cash that's owed back to a business; without a
verified account to send it to, that money has nowhere to go. Finance will
not process the money unless bank information is available and verified in
system


*Mandatory Aadhaar Verification for Riders*


All riders operating through the public network (including PPN) or
operating as loaned riders (PDR) must have a successfully Aadhaar-verified
profile.


Riders who are not Aadhaar verified will be automatically removed from the
public network and cannot rejoin until their verification is completed.
Additionally, vendors/CT teams will not be able to create future loan
shifts for unverified riders.



This requirement applies only to riders participating in the public network
or PDR. Captive riders fulfilling only your own business orders are not
impacted by this validation. Business KYC guidelines, which may be stricter
than just Aadhaar verification, apply to PDR.


A business receiving fulfilment from a public network rider has no other
way to vet that person, Aadhaar verification is the one check that travels
with the rider across accounts.


*Enterprise Accounts Gated On GST And Bank Verification*


Enterprise accounts will be created directly from the Admin Panel (V2), but
no new user can be added until both GST verification and bank verification
are complete. From 1 July, any Enterprise account without a valid GST on
file will be disabled. Existing Enterprise accounts are backfilled with GST
data ahead of this so nobody is caught off guard.


GST and bank details are what make Enterprise invoicing and settlement work
correctly, catching gaps at account creation is far cheaper than untangling
them after orders have already been billed. Additionally, once an
Enterprise account is GST verified, it will auto-populate the legal name
(and certain other fields) in the business name field (display only) to
ensure verified legal names are in place.
Account Structure & Hierarchy



*Parent Accounts Become View-Only Holding Entities*


A parent (Enterprise) account can no longer create orders, riders, routes,
or vehicles, those actions are hidden across the Orders, Routes, and Fleet
screens, leaving only the ability to view and download reports. All
operational work =E2=80=94 placing orders, managing riders, building routes=
, adding
vehicles =E2=80=94 now happens exclusively in the child accounts underneath=
 it.


A parent account's job is to oversee and configure the accounts beneath it,
not to run operations itself. Keeping that line clean stops assets from
ending up at the wrong level of the hierarchy. We will release more
features to make parent accounts even more powerful in the future as they
are expected to be holding/central entities.


*New Child Accounts Inherit The Parent's Rate Card And Wallet By Default*


Any new child account created under an Enterprise parent will, by default,
follow the parent's rate structure =E2=80=94 default or custom =E2=80=94 an=
d have its
wallet source set to the parent account, so charges are deducted from the
parent's wallet. This can still be overridden at the level of a single
charge type, so a child could follow the parent's rates everywhere except,
say, its own minimum guarantee, which it pays for itself.


Today every new child account needs its rates configured from scratch, and
that's exactly where mismatches and incorrect invoices come from.
Inheriting by default means a new account starts correct.
Billing & Invoicing



*B2B And B2C Accounts Now Get Separate Invoice Series*


Any account with GST details, including every Enterprise account by
default, is treated as B2B and billed on its own invoice series; accounts
without GST are B2C and billed on a separate one.


Splitting the series makes GST-relevant invoices easy to isolate for
filing, rather than having to pick them out of one mixed sequence.


*One Invoicing Period Per Hierarchy; Credit Limits Reserved For Enterprise*


A child account will always follow the parent's invoicing period (without
exception)


Non-enterprise accounts will be locked to monthly invoicing only with no
credit limit option available, which keeps them as wallet accounts by
definition. Enterprise accounts can choose weekly, fortnightly, or monthly
invoicing at the parent level, and credit limit options apply only there.


Mismatched invoicing periods within one parent-child hierarchy were a
recurring source of settlement confusion. Tying credit exposure to the
Enterprise tier also means it only applies to accounts that have already
cleared GST and bank verification.


*Child Accounts Without A GST Number Auto-Bill Under The Parent's GST*


If a child account doesn't have its own GST number, it's now automatically
billed under the parent account's GST instead of being clubbed as a
GST-less invoice. Defining a GST number at the child level becomes optional
rather than required, and the Admin Panel will clearly show whether a given
child's GST is inherited or set independently.


This keeps every invoice tied to a valid GST without forcing every child
account through its own GST setup, and removes the ambiguity that existed
when a child had no GST defined at all.


*New Accounts Default To Standard System Pricing*


Every new account created from 1 July follows the standard pricing model
shared earlier and defaults to system-defined rates rather than a blank or
ad-hoc setup. Custom rates can still be configured on top where they've
been negotiated, but the starting point is now consistent across every
account.


A consistent default removes the guesswork in pricing a brand-new account,
so every accounts starts from the same known baseline before any negotiated
rates are layered on.
Cash & Wallet Automation



*Cash Handling And Cash Remittance Fees Now Deduct Automatically*


Cash Handling Fee (for offline and online COD collection) and Cash
Remittance Fee (for cash a rider or admin remits to Pidge via UPI) now
deduct directly from the relevant wallet.


The business's wallet for handling fees, and the remitting party's wallet
for remittance fees, instead of going through a manual finance process.


Each fee can be configured as a flat amount, a percentage, or both, with
the higher of the two applied.


Two new reports, the Cash Handling Fee Report and the Cash Remittance Fee
Report, will be available under Wallet to track every deduction.


COD cash handling already shows up as ledger entries the moment it happens,
automating the fee against that same event removes the lag and manual
effort of finance applying it after the fact, and makes every deduction
auditable.



